Aim
To capture FTP login traffic using Wireshark and analyze plaintext username and password transmission over
the network.
Introduction
FTP (File Transfer Protocol) is used for transferring files between systems over a network. FTP transmits
usernames and passwords in plaintext, making it insecure.
Wireshark is used to capture and analyze FTP packets to observe login credentials and protocol
communication.
This experiment demonstrates the importance of secure protocols in cybersecurity.
Procedure
Step 1: Install Wireshark
1. Download and install Wireshark on Windows or Kali Linux.
2. Launch the Wireshark application.
Step 2: Start Packet Capture
1. Select the active network interface:
• Wi-Fi
• Ethernet
2. Double-click the interface to start capturing packets.
Step 3: Generate FTP Traffic
Open terminal and connect to an FTP server:
ftp test.rebex.net
Login credentials:
Username: demo
Password: password
Step 4: Apply FTP Filter
In Wireshark filter bar, enter:
ftp
Press Enter.
Step 5: Analyze FTP Packets
Observe:
• USER command
• PASS command
• Source IP address
• Destination IP address
• FTP communication packets
Implementation
FTP Command
ftp test.rebex.net
Wireshark Filter
ftp
Output
USER demo
PASS password
Analysis
Wireshark successfully captured FTP login traffic and displayed the username and password transmitted in
plaintext. This shows that FTP is insecure for sensitive communication.
Result
Thus, FTP login traffic was captured successfully using Wireshark and plaintext credential transmission was
analyzed.
